00:02:57.759 --> 00:02:59.600
And I have resources here on all of these.

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:01.839
They're on the slides linked if you want them later.

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:04.479
But OK, let's say you've done all that.

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:05.600
Now you're ready to go, right?

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:06.720
We're going to do code promotion.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:09.600
So the first thing you need is three environments.

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:12.320
You want a dev, a test, and a prod environment, right?

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:14.960
This is pretty, pretty, you've probably heard about this before.

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:17.199
We're going to get a little deeper into how to do it.

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:18.479
But dev, test, prod, right?

00:03:18.479 --> 00:03:19.679
You're going to develop stuff in dev.

00:03:19.679 --> 00:03:22.160
You're going to test it in test.

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:24.080
And prod is for production.

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:24.960
I have this little asterisk.

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:26.000
Sometimes two.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.839
Depending on your use case, you can kind of smush dev and test together, right?

00:03:29.839 --> 00:03:33.199
Those could be one environment where you do your development and your testing.

00:03:33.199 --> 00:03:36.160
But prod should definitely be its own place.

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:38.720
OK, so you need three environments.

00:03:39.679 --> 00:03:43.279
And so how are these environments different, right?

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:46.800
So one big difference is how easily can you make changes

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:48.000
in each of those environments, right?

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:48.639
In dev and test.

00:03:48.639 --> 00:03:50.720
In dev in particular, you want to be able to iterate quickly.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:52.399
You want to be able to try stuff out.

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:54.080
Prod, like no, right?

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:56.720
Only things that have been really validated go into prod.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:00.720
Additionally, the level of validation, which sort of goes along with that, right?

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:02.000
In dev, you're going to be trying things out.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:02.880
You're going to be testing them.

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:03.600
Things might work.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:04.240
They might break.

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:05.279
They might not work.

00:04:05.279 --> 00:04:05.839
That's fine.

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:06.960
It's a sandbox, right?

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:08.240
You want to be able to do that there.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:10.000
Stuff in prod, you want to have it validated.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.520
You validate it both for data science.

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:17.760
You need to validate both for the empirical correctness of what you're doing

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:19.440
and the code quality, right?

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:23.600
Like this is going to stand up to some sort of scrutiny, some sort of rigor.

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:27.440
And then the last thing that comes up a lot is sort of the realness of the analysis, right?

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:29.200
Are you accessing real data?

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:31.760
Or is it some sort of fake data that you have instead

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:34.959
because you don't want to have the real data in your dev environment?

00:04:34.959 --> 00:04:38.239
This is especially important if you're working with PII or PHI data, right?

00:04:38.239 --> 00:04:39.200
You've got to think about.

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:41.600
If you have a dev, that's great where you can use real data.

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:43.600
But it has to be really sandboxed in that case, right?

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:44.559
So you can't get anything out.

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:49.279
If you're doing writes from what you're doing, are you actually like you probably

00:04:49.279 --> 00:04:53.359
don't want to be doing your testing and accidentally writing to the real data?

00:04:53.359 --> 00:04:54.320
That's bad.

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:57.359
So you need to be able to figure out some way to not write to the real data

00:04:57.359 --> 00:04:58.559
as you're doing your development.

00:04:58.559 --> 00:05:02.559
And then the last piece is sort of like if you're doing things that take a while to run,

00:05:02.559 --> 00:05:05.440
it can be really annoying to have that happen as you're trying to iterate quickly

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:06.160
in your dev environment.

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:11.679
So you may want to do things like downsampling to be able to iterate quickly in dev in a way

00:05:11.679 --> 00:05:13.839
that you don't want to when you're going into production, obviously.

00:05:15.359 --> 00:05:18.239
So there's an R package called config.

00:05:18.239 --> 00:05:21.279
It's one of the little loved R packages.

00:05:21.279 --> 00:05:22.640
It's one of my favorites.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:23.920
Actually, I should have brought it.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:25.760
One of my colleagues made a hex sticker for it.

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:27.519
It has a fig on it, which I think is very clever.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:30.399
But it's a great package.

00:05:30.399 --> 00:05:32.559
It lets you sort of differentiate environments in a variety of ways.

00:05:32.559 --> 00:05:34.239
And we'll get into exactly how that works.

00:05:34.239 --> 00:05:38.079
But the basic idea is, as usual, there is a YAML file.

00:05:38.079 --> 00:05:39.600
Going to production is just like YAML.

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:41.279
It's just YAML all the way down.

00:05:41.279 --> 00:05:42.880
Just YAML on YAML on YAML.

00:05:42.880 --> 00:05:45.920
So you take some YAML, and you load the YAML into your R session.

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:47.040
And that's how you do config.

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:47.359
Great.

00:05:47.359 --> 00:05:47.600
Cool.

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:49.279
We'll get a little more into that in a minute.

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:51.040
So the second thing you need, then, is a mechanism.

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:52.000
You have your three environments.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.519
And you need a mechanism to go from one environment to the other to the other.

00:05:56.320 --> 00:06:00.559
And so the broad class of mechanisms, obviously, is something called CICD,

00:06:00.559 --> 00:06:02.640
Continuous Integration Continuous Deployment.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:03.920
You've almost certainly heard of it.

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:05.679
Some of you may have heard of it.

00:06:05.679 --> 00:06:07.200
And it sounds extremely intimidating.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:09.040
It is not so bad, I promise.

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:13.040
And in particular, today, I'm going to be talking a little bit about GitHub Actions,

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:15.600
which is one CICD tool.

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:18.399
I like it because it's really easy to use.

00:06:18.399 --> 00:06:20.640
If you use GitHub, it's already right there.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:24.799
But there are lots of other options, like GitLab, Azure DevOps, Jenkins.

00:06:24.799 --> 00:06:27.920
All of those are completely valid and work quite similarly.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:30.160
So I believe all of them are also YAML.

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:31.119
It's YAML all the way down.

00:06:31.679 --> 00:06:33.920
So how does CICD work?

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:35.760
You have your CICD stuff.

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:38.160
And it's watching your Git repo.

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:40.079
It's watching for things to happen.

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:41.839
Those are triggers.

00:06:41.839 --> 00:06:45.440
When those things get triggered, then it goes off and does something.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:46.559
And we'll get into what exactly that means.

00:06:46.559 --> 00:06:52.320
But usually, that something is either automated testing or a promotion from one place to another.

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:58.559
Those are usually the two things that are going to happen when your CICD pipeline is triggered.

00:06:58.720 --> 00:06:59.279
OK.

