to push it to the prod branch.

00:11:55.599 --> 00:11:58.799
So that's a pretty straightforward set of things.

00:11:58.799 --> 00:12:01.840
But how does it know how to do all that?

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:03.440
How is that what happens?

00:12:04.479 --> 00:12:07.119
That's what we're going to get into for the last eight minutes.

00:12:07.919 --> 00:12:12.799
OK, so first, let's look at what's going on here with the config package.

00:12:12.799 --> 00:12:15.200
Remember, I said config is just a bunch of YAML.

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:18.080
But we want to use it inside our R code.

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:19.359
I used it here to downsample.

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:22.320
So you can see I've got this config, config get.

00:12:23.119 --> 00:12:28.400
And when I do that, it loads up this config object.

00:12:29.599 --> 00:12:35.200
And you can see that that is just a bunch of variables.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:38.799
It's just a bunch of R entities.

00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:40.159
It's a list, named list.

00:12:41.039 --> 00:12:42.320
And so that's pretty useful.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:43.520
So now I can just use that in my code.

00:12:43.599 --> 00:12:47.039
So for example, here, where I'm slicing out part of the data,

00:12:47.039 --> 00:12:50.239
I'm taking half of it, in some cases, full in another.

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:52.559
And then I have the config name and that sort of thing.

00:12:52.559 --> 00:12:54.880
So again, how does it know to do this?

00:12:54.880 --> 00:12:57.119
Well, I've got my handy YAML file.

00:12:57.119 --> 00:12:58.320
It's YAML all the way down.

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:02.960
So in the YAML file, there are three definitions of environments.

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:06.479
There's default, test, and prod, corresponding to dev, test, and prod.

00:13:06.479 --> 00:13:09.119
In config, they use the term default, because that's sort of a fallback.

00:13:09.119 --> 00:13:10.320
It's not specified elsewhere.

00:13:10.799 --> 00:13:13.919
And you can see that in the default, in the dev place,

00:13:14.559 --> 00:13:18.000
I sample down to a half of the data set.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.000
I've also got it configured so that that goes to the test version of the report.

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:29.200
If I were to go to the test configuration, there I go up to a full one, all of the sample.

00:13:29.919 --> 00:13:35.440
And then in the prod version, I add going to the production version of the report.

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:38.719
So how does config know which package to pick up?

00:13:38.719 --> 00:13:44.960
Well, when I do config get, what this does is it looks at an environment variable.

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:45.760
It's in my environment.

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:48.559
And if you haven't spent a lot of time playing around with environment variables,

00:13:48.559 --> 00:13:53.840
they're a really crucial part of how configuring multiple environments work.

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:57.599
That is how things that are running know where they are,

00:13:57.599 --> 00:14:00.479
is by the environment variables that are set around them.

00:14:00.479 --> 00:14:03.119
So what I'm going to do is here, I'll manually, just to show you.

00:14:03.119 --> 00:14:13.039
sys.setenv, and we'll set the variable it uses by default is rconfig active.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.039
And I'm going to set it to be test.

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:21.840
So now when I set rconfig active to be test, and I'm going to run config get again,

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:23.840
you can see now I'm picking up the test config.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:26.799
You can see my sample fraction has updated to 1.

00:14:26.799 --> 00:14:29.119
And so it's just, if we think back about our YAML,

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:33.679
it's now selecting this middle block based on that environment variable that I had

00:14:33.679 --> 00:14:34.960
that is called test.

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:35.840
That's how config works.

00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:37.039
Like, that's the whole thing.

00:14:37.039 --> 00:14:41.520
It loads variables from a YAML file, depending on the value of an environment variable.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:45.119
It's like super simple, but really powerful if you have multiple environments

00:14:45.119 --> 00:14:46.960
and want different things to be true in each environment.

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:49.679
One other nice thing you can actually do is inside your config file,

00:14:49.679 --> 00:14:52.159
you can actually run our code as well, right?

00:14:52.159 --> 00:14:54.640
So these are all just like values that I'm typing here.

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:57.119
But if there's something you need to do that's a little more complex,

00:14:57.119 --> 00:15:00.239
you can actually run our code inside your config.

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:01.919
I don't recommend to do anything complicated,

00:15:01.919 --> 00:15:05.200
but sometimes it's useful to do other kinds of things.

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:08.799
Like, for example, sometimes you want to have a password that gets passed through

00:15:08.799 --> 00:15:11.119
but not appear in your config file, right?

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:13.760
You could do a get the password from an environment variable

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:16.159
and pass it right through inside your code.

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:19.520
OK, so that's the config piece of this, right?

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:21.679
That's the dividing up the environments.

00:15:21.679 --> 00:15:23.520
Now the GitHub part.

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:29.599
So by convention, in the .githubworkflows folder is where my GitHub actions go.

00:15:29.599 --> 00:15:32.559
And again, it's just YAML, YAML all the way down.

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:36.960
And so what you'll see is if you look in this YAML file,

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:39.599
it's all the things, right, if you remember.

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:42.479
Here, this is all the big headers, right?

00:15:42.479 --> 00:15:45.440
Set up quarto, install R, install R package dependencies.

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:47.359
These are those steps.

00:15:47.359 --> 00:15:48.960
They're just defined here, right?

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:49.679
That's all this does.

00:15:49.679 --> 00:15:51.039
It defines those steps.

00:15:51.119 --> 00:15:55.119
And what it does is it can use other actions that people have predefined for me, right?

00:15:55.119 --> 00:15:58.559
I can use the actions check out a repository action.

00:15:58.559 --> 00:16:04.000
I can use the quarto dev, right, that both GitHub and standalone people can define actions.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.880
So the quarto developers have defined a set up quarto action.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:09.840
The Rlib group has defined a set up R action.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:11.840
And it actually allows me to provide a variable, right?

00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:13.760
What version do I want?

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:16.640
I can also just run arbitrary code, right?

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:19.599
So I think Mark, right, you were talking about running R script, right?

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:26.239
I can run R script here right through GitHub actions by just telling it to run that R script.

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:28.479
So that's really useful.

00:16:28.479 --> 00:16:30.239
So that's what this action does.

00:16:30.239 --> 00:16:32.080
Now, how does it know, right?

00:16:32.080 --> 00:16:33.119
Again, this is the test one.

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:37.200
It knows it's the test one because I just have it set an environment variable here, right?

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:42.479
You can define environment variables inside the definitions for your GitHub actions flows.

00:16:42.479 --> 00:16:44.000
It works really nicely like that.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.440
And the last piece is when does this run?

00:16:46.159 --> 00:16:52.479
So this runs on a pull request when it opens or reopens, which is, right, that's what you would

00:16:52.479 --> 00:16:55.760
have seen if the Wi-Fi were being a little nicer.

00:16:55.760 --> 00:17:00.080
You would have seen that when I opened a pull request, the GitHub action checked off right

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:00.239
away.

00:17:00.239 --> 00:17:01.679
And that's my testing workflow.

00:17:01.679 --> 00:17:05.040
This is also a really common workflow if you're doing things like linting your code, right?

00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:06.319
You can put that in here.

00:17:06.319 --> 00:17:11.920
Doing things like running test suites, really great to put in a pull request triggered action.

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:14.719
And then there's another action, right?

00:17:14.719 --> 00:17:16.079
This one is identical.

00:17:16.079 --> 00:17:17.599
I will tell you, you can look through if you want to.

00:17:17.599 --> 00:17:20.719
But the only difference here is that it's using the prod config.

00:17:21.520 --> 00:17:24.560
And it runs actually on a push to the main branch, right?

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:28.000
And a completed merge is a push to the main branch, right?

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.760
So that's actually what it's really going to be triggered on.

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:34.959
You can do more complex things like nesting them with variables.

00:17:34.959 --> 00:17:36.800
But the syntax gets kind of complicated.

00:17:36.800 --> 00:17:41.520
And I didn't want to have to explain the syntax nor actually figure it out for myself.

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:42.959
So you can do that.

00:17:42.959 --> 00:17:45.680
But I just duplicated the same action twice.

00:17:47.119 --> 00:17:49.359
Just to show you a little bit of what these actions look like.

00:17:49.359 --> 00:17:53.119
So if you look, for example, this is the rlib actions setup r action.

00:17:53.119 --> 00:17:55.680
You can see they define all of these various variables.

00:17:55.680 --> 00:17:56.880
And I'll zoom in a little bit.

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:00.079
But you can see they give you the r version you can use.

00:18:00.079 --> 00:18:03.439
You can set the number of CPUs, all these kinds of things.

00:18:03.439 --> 00:18:04.400
You can set.

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:10.560
And they just sort of list them, right, in the help for that action.

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:16.319
I don't think this pushed at this point.

00:18:16.319 --> 00:18:17.280
But let's double check.

00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:18.719
Maybe we can show it real quick.

00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:19.920
No, still not pushing.

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:20.319
Oh, well.

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:23.040
Great.

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:27.520
So that was mostly what I wanted to show you today.

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:31.839
So just to recap a little bit of where we've been.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:33.119
OK.

00:18:34.079 --> 00:18:35.839
So the bottom line.

00:18:35.839 --> 00:18:40.239
Use config and environment variables to differentiate your different environments,

00:18:40.239 --> 00:18:41.119
right, one from the other.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:44.959
Use Git to manage when things move, right?

00:18:44.959 --> 00:18:46.880
The trigger is a Git branching strategy.

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:48.800
And so like I said back towards the beginning, right,

00:18:49.359 --> 00:18:52.479
having good Git practices is kind of a prerequisite for this,

00:18:52.479 --> 00:18:54.160
or at least something you should do along with this.

00:18:54.160 --> 00:18:57.520
Sometimes I see people where this is actually a really good motivation

00:18:57.520 --> 00:18:59.199
to set up good Git practices, right?

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:01.920
Like if your Git practices only matter because you're like,

00:19:01.920 --> 00:19:04.719
we're going to do Git, it's kind of hard to care.

00:19:04.719 --> 00:19:07.359
But if it's like, do good Git or else you're going to break the CICD,

00:19:07.359 --> 00:19:08.800
that's a much stronger motivator.

00:19:08.800 --> 00:19:10.400
Sometimes this can actually really go along nicely

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:15.040
if you're trying to get people to use Git in a more powerful and intentional way.

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:18.800
And then use CICD GitHub Actions to do promotion mechanics.

00:19:19.599 --> 00:19:23.920
Since I do work for Posit, I would be remiss if I didn't just say that Posit,

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:24.959
I'm so used to saying RStudio.

00:19:24.959 --> 00:19:26.719
It's very hard to change my language.

00:19:26.719 --> 00:19:27.760
It's been really difficult.

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:31.359
Posit Connect can do parts of this for you, right?

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:35.040
Connect can do the thing where it watches the Git repo

00:19:35.040 --> 00:19:36.479
and picks up the changes for you.

00:19:36.479 --> 00:19:38.160
So you don't have to have a GitHub Action.

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:40.160
That's personally my favorite feature of Connect,

00:19:40.719 --> 00:19:42.400
is that it can do that part for you.

